author: Kat Johnson
title: Explore How Data Lineage Maps Your Data's Journey to Foster Data-Driven Decisions | HackerNoon
text: As it is rightly said, data is the lifeblood of any organization in the digital landscape. Businesses depend heavily on data to make data-driven informed decisions. Have you ever wondered how businesses can ensure that data quality is up to mark and meets required standards? Ensuring the quality and accuracy of data is paramount. How convenient would it be if we could determine the source, pathway, and destination of data, that is having access to the complete history of the data? This is where the concept of Data Lineage comes in! Data lineage is a process of tracking the flow of data, offering a holistic and clear view of data flow from source to destination and what data changes had been there in between. Understanding Data Lineage Better To understand data lineage better, compare it with a map, which directs the users step by step on what direction to take to reach the destination. Similarly, data lineage is a GPS but for data. It facilitates various stakeholders to make better decisions by having the complete history of data. Why Does Data Lineage Matter? Let's Witness Why There Is a Need for Data Lineage- To improve data literacy and observability, Dependency of Various Stakeholders In order to perform tasks supremely well, data management and IT professionals must have to understand data patterns and the history of the data, as it serves as a foundation for further activities to carry on. Technical and operational metadata, impact and root-cause analysis along data chains, and impact analysis, all require a clear understanding of data lineage. Fulfilling Regulatory Compliance Requirement By offering a comprehensive view of data movement, storage, and transformation, data lineage helps organizations to check who has access to data, and what data changes have been made over time, overall offering a complete record of the data pathway. This proactive approach helps in identifying potential risks associated with data alterations. Moreover, during compliance auditing and documentation, following data lineage can offer insights to regulators to ensure adherence to regulatory compliances. To Boost Transparency by Enhancing Data Quality and Integrity To ensure that data is trustworthy, accurate, and aligned with business objectives, data lineage helps maintain data quality throughout its pipeline by offering a transparent view of the data. By tracking the flow of data, organizations can identify and address data-related quality issues. To Identify Debugs and Troubleshooting Errors It‚Äôs of utmost importance to identify debugs and errors at an early stage, to ensure that decisions are made of accurate and reliable data. Data lineage can identify inconsistencies, troubleshooting errors, and anomalies in the data, to help developers track changes and go back to the previous version of data if an error occurs after the alteration in the data. To Better Manage Data-Related Risks Data lineage simplifies risk management by offering insights regarding how data is transformed across the organization. Understanding the lineage of critical data facilitates organizations to eliminate or better tackle data breaches, misuse, and data loss. Such practice enables the implementation of appropriate security measures to protect confidential data. Making Data Suitable for Business Intelligence and Analytics It would not be wrong to say that today every organization wants to know the analytics for obvious reasons, that is to land on smarter decision-making. For this purpose, data lineage is essential for business intelligence and analytics to act upon and ensure that decisions are based on statistics and analytics rather than gut instinct. Summing Up From the above need for data lineage, it's evident that having a comprehensive knowledge of data flow is of utmost importance to crack the decision-making game. It serves as a backbone for propelling trust and transparency in your data by understanding the journey of the data. In a nutshell, knowing data through data lineage is the need of the hour to address data-related risks and issues. author: Sophie Lin - Technology Editor
title: Leaked Details on S11 Chip Show Limited Performance Gains for 2025 Apple Watches
text:
Apple Watch Series 11 Chip May Lack Major Performance Boost The upcoming Apple Watch series 11, Apple Watch ultra 3, and Apple Watch SE 3 are expected to feature an updated S11 system-in-package (SiP), but don‚Äôt expect a significant leap in processing power, according to recently surfaced internal information.
The details suggest the S11 chip will retain the same T8310 architecture as the S9 and S10 chips found in the Series 9 and Series 10 Apple Watch models. This is not entirely unexpected, as Apple has a history of reusing core technology across multiple generations of its S-series chips.The S6, S7, and S8 chips, for exmaple, all shared the same fundamental architecture.
The S9 and S10 chips are built with two ‚ÄúSawtooth‚Äù performance cores, similar to those in the A16 Bionic chip. Despite the older tech, this architecture delivers ample power for a wrist-worn device, offering a 64-bit dual-core processor, a 4-core Neural Engine, second-generation Ultra Wideband (UWB) support, and 64GB of storage.

author: Anna Louise
title: Extreme Weather Changes Put Pressure on Animals And Plants in UK | Nature World News
text: Climate change is putting pressure on animals and plants in the United Kingdom due to rising average temperatures, shifting seasons, and increasingly unpredictable weather, according to the National Trust's annual report. Effects of Extreme Weather on Animals And Plants The conservation charity said the changing weather patterns, notably the rising temperatures, are upsetting nature and the regular rhythm of the seasons. This lack of predictability disrupts animal behavior in particular, but it can also have an influence on trees and plants. The National Trust listed a long number of species that have perished in the past year, including oak trees, which are becoming increasingly vulnerable to the oak processionary moth's caterpillars, which infest them. Because of a lack of extended cold spells in recent years, the moths have moved northward from their natural Mediterranean environment. Because of the milder winters, hibernators such as dormice are waking up too early and depleting crucial energy stores. It is also causing red deer rutting to occur later, resulting in calves being born in the summer rather than the spring, with inadequate time to mature and store fat stores for survival. According to the trust, some of the rare lichens and liverworts that thrive in the temperate rainforest at Lydford Gorge, on the outskirts of Dartmoor in Devon, died last winter due to a lack of water. When the severe rains arrived, water voles were driven from their burrows, putting them at risk of cold, hunger, and predation. "These baseline changes that we're seeing are really worrying and what we should be taking more notice of, particularly when combined with extreme weather events, which makes things even more challenging," said [Ben McCarthy](https://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/uknews/climate-change-has-caused-chaos-for-uk-nature-in-2023/ar-AA1m4rwy), the head of nature and restoration ecology at the National Trust. Read Also: [Obama Administration Releases Plan to Help Animals Adapt to Climate Change](https://www.natureworldnews.com/articles/1045/20130327/obama-administration-releases-plan-help-animals-adapt-clim.htm) Government's Urgent Action The conservation organization is pushing lawmakers to prioritize "urgent action" to safeguard the environment and people from future climate shocks, adding that parties should pledge to make changes in their manifestos for the next UK general election. McCarthy stressed they want to see parties commit to accelerating work on [environment restoration](https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2023/dec/27/weather-changes-causing-chaos-for-uk-flora-and-fauna-says-national-trust-audit?fbclid=IwAR2fFylsllOEFooj-_6fyA_k9Jc5x8IRevRkyVMdOTn5mBSuY6UFizdNixI), expanding support for nature-based climate change solutions, and putting climate adaptation at the core of their manifestos so that the UK is better prepared for the increasing weather extremes. "We need to see more action from politicians, particularly as we enter this election year, to ensure tackling the nature and climate crisis is a top priority," he added. The [National Trust](https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/) has been working on programs to make the landscape more robust and adaptable to changing seasons, warning that we must be prepared for this "new norm." However, the audit revealed some rays of hope, with a record-breaking number of Cornish Chough birds identified this year, a 60% rise over the previous year, having previously been extinct in Cornwall. Beavers in Somerset welcomed their first kits, welcoming in twins and expanding the beaver community on the Holnicote Estate. Moreover, despite heavy rain from Storm Babet damaging four of the beavers' dams, the family was quick to begin repairs due to their hardworking attitude.
